pullRequest.body:
I loogled for every occurrence of `"cast", Nat` and `"natCast"` and where the casted nat was `n`, and made sure there were corresponding `@[simp]` lemmas for `0`, `1`, and `OfNat.ofNat n`. This is necessary in general for simp confluence. Example:

```lean
import Mathlib

variable {α : Type*} [LinearOrderedRing α] (m n : ℕ) [m.AtLeastTwo] [n.AtLeastTwo]

example : ((OfNat.ofNat m : ℕ) : α) ≤ ((OfNat.ofNat n : ℕ) : α) ↔ (OfNat.ofNat m : ℕ) ≤ (OfNat.ofNat n : ℕ) := by
  simp only [Nat.cast_le] -- this `@[simp]` lemma can apply

example : ((OfNat.ofNat m : ℕ) : α) ≤ ((OfNat.ofNat n : ℕ) : α) ↔ (OfNat.ofNat m : α) ≤ (OfNat.ofNat n : α) := by
  simp only [Nat.cast_ofNat] -- and so can this one

example : (OfNat.ofNat m : α) ≤ (OfNat.ofNat n : α) ↔ (OfNat.ofNat m : ℕ) ≤ (OfNat.ofNat n : ℕ) := by
  simp -- fails! `simp` doesn't have a lemma to bridge their results. confluence issue.
```

As far as I know, the only file this PR leaves with `ofNat` gaps is `PartENat.lean`. #8002 is addressing that file in parallel.

This got a bad name during porting it seems
```suggestion
theorem of_natCast (n : ℕ) : of A 0 n = n :=
```
I think you should add it anyway, without marking it `simp`
Nit: stray blank line
I think this should be a `/--` comment so that it appears in the docs.
I think this might have been a hack to ensure the implicit argument to `Eq` was really `NNRat` and not `Subtype _`
I would be surprised if it could implicitly turn into `Subtype _` because `NNRat` is not `reducible`. Was this more of a risk in Lean 3?
It turns into `Subtype` because `⟨_, _⟩` is notation for `Subtype.mk` which has the wrong return type.

Ah so this is the elusive difference between `(x : α)` and `@id α x`. Unless the former triggers a coercion, it just asserts that the type of `x` is defeq to `α`, whereas the latter actually transforms the type of the term. Is this defeq abuse a sign that this is a bad lemma and there should be `mk` function in the API of `ℚ≥0`? And I suppose using `@id ℚ≥0` or `show ℚ≥0 from` would both be inappropriate here because this is the rhs of a simp lemma so needs to be fully simplified.. (I've reverted the change to this line for now)

I think this lemma is reasonable, but it does suggest a flaw in the API (which is out of scope for this PR). If you don't like the `@Eq` approach, I think something like `(by exact ⟨_,_⟩) = _` will also assign the type correctly
Was the conclusion that they could?
In fact that they couldn't! I forgot to go back and prove them
Is there a reason you reordered this lemma?
To prove it with `Nat.cast_lt`, which requires `CharZero`

Does this actually work as intended?
I would think that the `p` if it was a raw nat lit would appear in `CharP` as an `ofNat` too.
I also worry a bit about making the whole LHS of a simp lemma no index, if that ends up matching everything in the discrimination tree I wonder if we would see a performance impact for simp if we have too many of them
From local testing, the simp lemma as written does seem to fire with `ZMod 5`, for example. It also works if I change it to `[CharP R (OfNat.ofNat p)]`.
I worry this lemma might be responsible for the performance hit.

Yes, this seems like a bad simplification rule, since this simplification rule tries to match against every subexpression, IIUC. There are also a some other simplification lemmas whose pattern seems too general, and will be pretty expensive, like `ofNat_le`.

But mostly these new simp lemmas are great!
Hmm but this lemma is necessary for simp confluence. Should I replace this with a TODO that mentions the no_index library note?

simp confluence is important to have, but is it worth it if it makes simp (much) slower? 

I'm wondering if we should start a small list of additional simp sets, that you can opt-in to, e.g. `simp [confluence]` is a simp-set where we try really hard to be confluent.
I removed `@[simp]` and added a TODO for now. Hopefully we can make this `simp` once the core bug requiring `no_index` is fixed (https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/issues/2867)
Why do we need the `AddMonoidWithOne` instance, it's implied immediately by the `Semiring` instance below.
Aren't these three covered by `NeZero`? Or do we not have the instance from `AtLeastTwo` to `NeZero`?
I don't think there is such an instance. I'll investigate adding that and removing these lemmas.

Adding `import Mathlib.Algebra.NeZero` triggered this `assert_not_exists`. What's the right way to address this error?

https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/4acfd8a235ca7c92ee2dc6d96d12a96aafcbddc7/Mathlib/Algebra/Field/Defs.lean#L178-L181

Also, `NeZero.one_le` didn't exist, so I had to add it. The code where these `NeZero` lemmas are used seems a bit less uniform now with each lemma looking a bit different to use:
- `(NeZero.ne n)` and `(NeZero.pos n)`
- `NeZero.one_le`
- `Nat.AtLeastTwo.ne_one` and `Nat.AtLeastTwo.one_lt`
- `Nat.AtLeastTwo.prop`

Would it be worth keeping these lemmas all under `Nat.AtLeastTwo` for uniformity? Maybe it doesn't matter since `exact?` can find all of them..
I solved the import error by moving this instance to a later file
Arguably we need versions with `ofNat` on one side and `Nat.cast` on the other too...
Good point. Will add

```suggestion · rw [← Nat.cast_succ, lt_omega] ```

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion (f : F) (h : f 1 = 1) (n : ℕ) [n.AtLeastTwo] : f (OfNat.ofNat n) = OfNat.ofNat n := ```
I've split this change to #10953

I think I'd like to see this change, along with the other API changes around `AtLeastTwo`, split to its own PR. I don't think it's particularly controversial, but i'd rather it not be hidden amidst an otherwise-mechanistic patch.
Makes sense! Done at #10964.
This would go into the same split PR I describe above.
Is this still true in the lastest version?
Please check this is still needed too
